Is Taylor Swift really a musician talented enough to be among the best in history?

Best musician? No. Best entertainer? Yes. By strictly musical standards, a lot of people are equal or better; but she gives her fans the show that they want to see, and she treats them great, and she handles her off-stage life with wicked smarts.

Relatively few people judge a performer on their musical skills alone. They want to be entertained, and she gives them that.

Why did Taylor Swift become so successful with a victim mentality?

You sure about that?

Here’s the thing — if you go watch the NPR Tiny Desk Concert she did, she talks a bit about writing breakup songs. She was writing them before she’d ever had a real relationship. It’s something she legitimately enjoys. No one would question this if she was a male performer (thus, “The Man”). But instead, she justified it with a string of staged relationships that gave her a reputation she doesn’t seem super happy about; she’s backed away from it since she went pop and apparently wrote “Death By A Thousand Cuts” just to prove to herself that she still had the knack for it.
